 techniques of citizenship. These tools of political friendship, Allen contends, can help us become more trustworthy to others and overcome the fossilized distrust among us. Sacrifice is the key concept that bridges citizenship and trust, according to Allen. She uncovers the ordinary, daily sacrifices citizens make to keep democracy working—and offers methods for recognizing and reciprocating those sacrifices. Trenchant, incisive, and ultimately hopeful, Talking to Strangers is nothing less than a manifesto for a revitalized democratic citizenry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCultural pluralism. 0aPolitical participation. 0aPolitical science. 0aSocial sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acitizenship, american culture, united states of america, usa, brown v board, humanities, social thought, race, racism, civic education, interracial distrust, alienation, suspicion, little rock, elizabeth eckford, hazel bryan, philosophy, political science, personal reflections, chicago, trustworthy, sacrifice, democratic citizenry, democracy, participation, intergroup relations, cultural pluralism, rhetoric, brotherhood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022601466140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226014685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226014685/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles